observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our previous years' recommendations:

The responsible AOs immediately liquidate their existing CAs with the CAD and/or refund the same to the City Treasurer's Office;

The City Legal Officer issue a final demand letter to erring AOs and institute available judicial remedies to recover the unliquidated CAs, more particularly to those CAs from CY 2011 and prior years;

The City Accountant –

Withhold the salary of erring AOs who failed to liquidate their CAs after the final demand from the City Legal Office;

Issue a certification that all previous CAs for a particular AO have been fully settled before the grant of subsequent CAs;

Ensure that all CAs are fully liquidated at the end of each year;

The City Accountant and the City Legal Officer consider the provisions of Sections 8.1 to 8.3 of COA Circular No. 2016-05, dated December 19, 2016, for the writing-off of the accounts of those unliquidated CAs whose AOs have passed away or liquidation thereof is highly improbable;

The Internal Audit Services Department (IASD) reviews the existing policy of the City in the granting, utilization, and liquidation of CAs and, if possible, institute additional measures to provide for more efficient and effective procedures to ensure that CAs granted are immediately liquidated within the required period; and

The City Treasurer evaluates the necessity of designating additional AOs to eliminate the granting of multiple CAs to payroll officers.

We recommended that the CAD:

Foster effective communication and better coordination among the account officers maintaining the books of the three funds to ensure that any transaction affecting the Due from/Due to Other Funds accounts is appropriately recorded on both ends to avoid any lag and discrepancy in recording;

Review the breakdown of the beginning balances to identify the causes of discrepancies and conduct reconciliation of reciprocal accounts to eliminate, if not minimize, the unreconciled balances and prepare the necessary adjusting entries; and;

If the breakdown of beginning balances cannot be further identified after exerting all efforts, consider requesting the write-off of the dormant reciprocal accounts, subject to compliance with the requirements of COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We recommended that:

The CHRMD – 

Coordinate with CAD on the reconciliation of Due to GSIS account to determine the cause of the over-remittances and unremitted premium contributions and loan amortizations in CY 2023;


The CHRMD immediately process the remittance of the identified unremitted GSIS premium contributions in CY 2023

The CAD – 

Submit immediately a written explanation for the identified deficiencies;


Coordinate with CHRMD on the reconciliation of Due to GSIS account to determine the cause of the over-remittances and unremitted premium contributions and loan repayments in CY 2023; 


Ensure that all transactions during the year are being recorded in the books to conform with generally accepted accounting principles and follow pertinent laws and regulations; and

Submit adjusting journal entries, if any, to correct the Due to GSIS account balance as of December 31, 2023.

We recommended and Management agreed that:
The CLD issue a final demand letter to erring AOs and institute available judicial remedies to recover the unliquidated CAs;
The CAD –
Withhold the salary of erring AOs still connected with the City Government, who failed to liquidate their CAs after the final demand from the CLD;
Issue a certification that all previous CAs for a particular AO have been fully settled prior to the grant of any CA;
Ensure that all CAs are fully liquidated at the end of each year;
The Internal Audit Services Department (IASD) review the existing policy of the City in the granting, utilization, and liquidation of CAs and, if possible, institute additional measures to provide more efficient and effective procedures to ensure that CAs granted are timely liquidated within the required period;
The City Treasurer evaluate the necessity of designating additional AOs to eliminate the granting of multiple CAs to payroll officers; and
Henceforth, strictly comply with the provisions of Section 89 of PD No.1445 COA Circular No. 97-002 and COA Circular No. 2012-004 on the granting, utilization, and liquidation of CAs.

We recommended and Management agreed that:
The CAD –
Reconcile the balance of the Due to BIR account to determine whether said balance represents an unremitted/over-remitted amount or error in recording in the books, and make the necessary actions/adjustments to bring the Due to BIR account to its normal balance, whichever is applicable;
Conduct regular review, reconciliation, and proper monitoring of taxes withheld and remitted to ensure the correctness and accuracy of the Due to BIR account balance;
Revisit all payments for government projects with advance payments to determine whether the advance payments are subjected to tax and prepare the necessary adjustments in the Due to BIR account, if any;
b. The CAD and City Information and Communications Technology Department (CICTD) coordinate in updating the account codes currently being used and align them with the actual codes used in remitting the taxes to the BIR as indicated in the tax returns for easy reconciliation and proper monitoring of taxes withheld and remitted;
The IASD establish internal control measures to avoid errors in recording transactions related to BIR taxes withheld; and
Henceforth, strictly comply with the provisions of Section 112 of PD No. 1445, COA Circular No. 2015-009, dated December 1, 2015, BIR RMC No. 23-2007, dated March 20, 2007, BIR RMC No. 10-2018, dated January 31, 2018, and Title X of the NIRC of 1997.

We recommended and Management agreed that:
The CHRMD and CAD coordinate on the reconciliation of Due to GSIS account to determine the cause of the over-remittances and the unremitted premium contributions and loan amortizations in CY 2024 and prior years;
The CHRMD immediately process the remittance of the identified unremitted GSIS premium contributions in CY 2024 and prior years;
The CAD ensure that all transactions during the year are correctly recorded in the books to conform with the generally accepted accounting principles and follow pertinent laws, rules and regulations; and
Henceforth, ensure compliance with COA Circular No. 2015-009, Sections 4(1) and 112 of PD No. 1445, and the relevant provisions RA No. 8291, or the GSIS Act of 1997 and its IRR.

We recommended and Management agreed that:
The CHRMD and CAD –
Coordinate for the reconciliation of the beginning balance of Due to Pag-IBIG account to determine whether said balance represents an unremitted/over-remitted amount or error in recording in the books, and make the necessary remittance/action to the Pag-IBIG or proper adjustments in the books, whichever is applicable;
Determine the source of unremitted loan repayments withheld from the three dormant accounts and make the necessary remittance to the Pag-IBIG or proper adjustments in the books, whichever is applicable;
Review the process of determining the amount due for Inter-Agency Payables, identify the gaps/issues in recording, and take the necessary corrective actions to harmonize the processes between the two departments; and
Henceforth, ensure compliance with Section 112 of PD No. 1445, COA Circular No. 2015-009, HDMF Law of 2009 and its IRR, and Section E, Paragraph 4 of HDMF Circular No. 275, series of 2010.

We recommended and Management agreed that the CHRMD and CAD:
Create a detailed plan outlining the steps needed to reconcile the records, including specific tasks, timelines, and responsible parties. The plan should prioritize the most significant discrepancies;
Expedite the reconciliation of the beginning balance of the Due to PhilHealth account to determine whether said balance represents an unremitted/over-remitted amount or error in recording in the books, and make the necessary remittance/action to the PhilHealth or proper adjustments in the books, whichever is applicable;
Communicate with PhilHealth to address any outstanding issues and review the process of determining the amount due for Inter-Agency Payables. Identify the gaps/issues in recording and take the necessary corrective actions to harmonize the processes between the two departments; and
Henceforth, ensure compliance with Section 18(b), Rule III, Title III of the Revised IRR of the National Health Insurance Act of 2013, PhilHealth Circular No. 0001 s. 2014 dated January 9, 2014, Section 112 of PD No. 1445, and COA Circular No. 2015-009.

We commended Management for its compliance with the preparatory stage and the data gathering, vulnerability assessment, risk analysis, and validation stage of LCCAP in CY 2024. However, we recommended and Management agreed that:
The City Budget Department (CBD) ensure the integration of climate change-responsive PPAs in the annual budget in accordance with 5.1.1 and 5.1.6 of DBM-CCC-DILG JMC No. 2015-01;
The CPDD ensure proper identification and tagging of climate change-responsive PPAs in the AIP in compliance with Item 4.2 and Annex A of DBM-CCC-DILG JMC No. 2015-01;
The LCCAP Core Team properly monitor and evaluate the implementation of the climate change action plans and programs of the City and submit an annual progress report on the implementation of the local action plan in response to climate change to the CCC as required under Section 20 of RA No. 9729.; and
Henceforth, ensure the effective implementation of the framework strategy and programs on climate change and comply with the provisions of RA No. 9729, DILG MC No. 2014-135, and DBM-CCC-DILG JMC No. 2015-01.

We recommended that the City:

Consider increasing the personnel complement of the CAD by hiring staff with adequate and appropriate qualifications; and;

Constitute a Barangay Team by way of appropriate appointment/ designation whose functions would pertain to the provision of accounting services for the Barangays of the City.

We recommended that:

The CHRMD – 

Request for the latest SOA or confirmation with HDMF to determine if there are unremitted contributions withheld in the current and prior years;

Once SOA or confirmation from HDMF is available, coordinate with CAD on the reconciliation of Due to Pag-IBIG account to determine the cause of over-remittance and eliminate the variances; 

Immediately process the remittance of the identified unremitted. Pag-IBIG contributions and loan repayments in CY 2022.


The ICD establish internal control measures to avoid errors in recording transactions related to Pag-IBIG contributions and loan repayments withheld and remittances.

We reiterated our previous years' recommendation that Management requires:

The responsible Accountable Officers (AOs) to immediately liquidate their existing CAs with the CAD and/or refund the same to the City Treasurer's Office;

The City Legal Officer to issue a final demand letter to erring AOs and institute available judicial remedies to recover the unliquidated CAs, more particularly those CAs from CY 2011 and prior years;

The City Accountant to withhold the salary of erring AOs who failed to liquidate their CAs after the final demand from the City Legal Office;

The City Accountant and City Legal Officer to consider the provisions of 
Sections 8.1 to 8.3 of COA Circular No. 2016-05 dated December 19, 2016, for the writing-off of the accounts of those unliquidated CAs whose Aos are deceased or liquidation thereof is highly improbable;

The Internal Audit Division to review the existing policy of the City in the granting, utilization, and liquidation of CAs, and if possible, institute additional measures to provide for more efficient and effective procedures to ensure that CAs granted are immediately liquidated within the required period;

The City Accountant to ensure that all CAs are fully liquidated at the end of each year; and

Strict compliance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 and COA Circular No. 2012-004.

We recommended that:

The City Human Resource Management Department (CHRMD) – 

Coordinate with CAD on the reconciliation of Due to GSIS account to determine the cause of unremitted contributions withheld and loan repayments in CY 2022; 

Immediately process the remittance of the identified unremitted GSIS contributions and loan repayments in 
CY 2022;

The CAD – 

Coordinate with CHRMD on the reconciliation of Due to GSIS account to determine the cause of unremitted contributions and loan repayments in CY 2022; 

Submit adjusting journal entry, if any, to correct the Due to GSIS account balance, as of 
December 31, 2022, after reconciliation; and

Henceforth, Management ensures compliance with the relevant provisions under the GSIS Act of 1997 and its IRR.

We reiterated our previous years' recommendations:
The responsible AOs immediately liquidate their existing CAs with the CAD and/or refund the same to the City Treasurer's Office;
The City Legal Officer issue a final demand letter to erring AOs and institute available judicial remedies to recover the unliquidated CAs, more particularly to those CAs from CY 2011 and prior years;
The City Accountant –
Withhold the salary of erring AOs who failed to liquidate their CAs after the final demand from the City Legal Office;
Issue a certification that all previous CAs for a particular AO have been fully settled before the grant of subsequent CAs;
Ensure that all CAs are fully liquidated at the end of each year;
The City Accountant and the City Legal Officer consider the provisions of Sections 8.1 to 8.3 of COA Circular No. 2016-05, dated 
December 19, 2016, for the writing-off of the accounts of those unliquidated CAs whose AOs have passed away or liquidation thereof is highly improbable;
The Internal Audit Services Department (IASD) reviews the existing policy of the City in the granting, utilization, and liquidation of CAs and, if possible, institute additional measures to provide for more efficient and effective procedures to ensure that CAs granted are immediately liquidated within the required period; and
The City Treasurer evaluates the necessity of designating additional AOs to eliminate the granting of multiple CAs to payroll officers.

Direct the CAD to assess the collectability of the balance Due from GOCCs – PhilHealth account as of December 31, 2023, by preparing an aging schedule and assessing the carrying amount under IPSAS 29, Paragraphs 67 and 72;
Direct the MCMC PhilHealth Section to assist and coordinate with the CAD in the preparation of the aging schedule and in conducting the assessment of the collectability of the recorded balance Due from GOCCs – PhilHealth account; and
Require the Head of MCMC to communicate with PhilHealth Regional Office to carry out the requirements of items 3 to 7, Section V-A of PhilHealth Circular No. 2023-0028 and confirm the correct balance of Due from GOCCs – PhilHealth of the City as of December 31, 2023.

We recommended that:
The CHRMD –
Coordinate with CAD on the reconciliation of Due to GSIS account to determine the cause of the over-remittances and unremitted premium contributions and loan amortizations in CY 2023;
Immediately process the remittance of the identified unremitted GSIS premium contributions in CY 2023;
The CAD –
Submit immediately a written explanation for the identified deficiencies;
Coordinate with CHRMD on the reconciliation of Due to GSIS account to determine the cause of the over-remittances and unremitted premium contributions and loan repayments in CY 2023;
Ensure that all transactions during the year are being recorded in the books to conform with generally accepted accounting principles and follow pertinent laws and regulations; and
Submit adjusting journal entries, if any, to correct the Due to GSIS account balance as of December 31, 2023.

We recommended that Management:

Remit all unremitted premium contributions withheld in CY 2021; 


Record financial transactions timely in the books of accounts, especially remittances to PhilHealth, to conform with Section 112 of PD No. 1445.

We recommended that:
The CAD –
Retrieve the documents/information/records as early as CY 2008 until the present to serve as the basis for the correction/adjustment of the reconciling items. In case of no avail, request before this Office copies of the required documents/information/record if the same were originally submitted hereto;
Upon retrieval of the necessary documents/information/records, draw journal entry vouchers to record all valid reconciling items that require adjustment and/or correction in the books;
Reconcile the balances of CIB-LCCA and CIB-LCSA with the adjusted bank balances per BRS;
The CTD transmit the transaction documents to CAD on a constant and timely basis to facilitate the immediate reconciliation of accounting and treasury records and to avoid the recurrence of this observation;
Henceforth, strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular 
No. 96-011 relative to the preparation of BRS.

We recommended the following:
The CAD –
Retrieve the documents/information/records as early as necessary to serve as the basis for the correction/adjustment of the reconciling items;
Upon retrieval of the necessary documents/ information/ records, draw journal entry vouchers to record all valid reconciling items that require adjustment and/or correction in the books;
The CTD prepare a cashbook for the non-moving SL (Other LGUs) as required by the Revised Cash Examination Manual and the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
The CTD and the CAD bilaterally reconcile the balances of SLs with the balances of the cashbook and immediately effect the necessary correction;
Henceforth, strictly adhere to the Revised Cash Examination Manual and MNGAS for LGUs relative to the preparation of cashbooks and the reconciliation with accounting records.

We reiterated our previous year's recommendation that Management:
Require the responsible AOs to immediately liquidate their existing CAs with the CAD and/or refund the same to the City Treasurer’s Office;
The City Legal Officer to issue a final demand letter to erring AOs and institute available judicial remedies to recover the unliquidated CAs, more particularly to those CAs from 2011 and prior years;
Require the City Accountant to withhold the salary of erring AOs who failed to liquidate their CAs after the final demand from the City Legal Office;
The City Accountant and City Legal Officer to consider the provisions of Sections 8.1 to 8.3 of COA Circular No. 2016-05, dated December 19, 2016, for the writing-off of the accounts of those unliquidated CAs whose AOs have passed away or liquidation thereof is highly improbable;
Require the Internal Audit Division to review the existing policy of the City in the granting, utilization, and liquidation of CAs, and if possible, institute additional measures to provide for more efficient and effective procedures to ensure that CAs granted are immediately liquidated within the required period;
The City Accountant to ensure that all CAs are fully liquidated at the end of each year; and
Strictly comply with COA Circular No. 97-002 and COA Circular 
No. 2012-004.

We recommended that the LSB:
Prepare the Three-Year Strategic Plan under the provisions of the Joint Circular, and submit the same to this Office for verification and audit;
Prepare the SEF Annual Budget using Annex A of the Joint Circular and based on the three-year strategic plan and DepEd-approved School Improvement Plan (SIP) and Division Education Development Plan (DEDP);
Strictly monitor the implementation of all planned PPAs under the SEF to ensure 100% attainment of the needs for the operation and maintenance of public schools within the City; and
Henceforth, strictly observe the guidelines on the appropriation and utilization of the SEF under DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017 and DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 2, s. 2020.

We recommended that Management:
Remit all unremitted premium contributions withheld in CY 2021;
Require the CHRD and CAD to reconcile their records of Due to PhilHealth account, ascertain if there are unremitted balances pertaining thereto and remit the same or, in case of discrepancies in the account balance, effect appropriate adjustments to the account to correct the balance per books;
Record financial transactions timely in the books of accounts, especially remittances to PhilHealth, to conform with Section 112 of PD No. 1445; and
Henceforth, strictly comply with Section 18(b), Rule III, Title III of the Revised IRR of the National Health Insurance Act and PhilHealth Circular No. 0001, s.2014, on the New Payment Schedule for Premium Contributions.

We recommended that Management:
Submit a written explanation/justification on the non-moving Due to GSIS subsidiary ledger accounts in CY 2021, and thereafter determine if the non-moving Due to GSIS subsidiary ledger accounts in CY 2021 are, in fact, unremitted premium contributions and loan repayments or accounts requiring reconciliation and adjustment;
Remit all withheld/unremitted premium contributions and loan repayments withheld in CY 2021;
Require the CHRD and CAD to reconcile their records of Due to GSIS account, ascertain if there are unremitted balances pertaining thereto and remit the same or, in case of discrepancies in the account balance, effect appropriate adjustments to the account to correct the balance per books; and,
Henceforth, strictly comply with Sections 14.1, 14.2, 14.3, 15, 16.1 and 59.5 of RA No. 8291, or The Government Service Insurance System Act of 1997, and its Implementing Rules and Regulations.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the City Accounting Department to –
immediately conduct further analysis to determine the nature of unremitted taxes totaling P30,115,264.29, and upon verification, prepare the necessary documentation to settle all unremitted taxes withheld as required under the Revenue Memorandum Circular to avoid being subjected to penalties, interests and surcharges by the BIR;
analyze further taxes withheld and remitted in prior years to determine the nature and causes of the negative balance of the three per cent EWT under the GF amounting to P6,005,805.79 as of December 31, 2021, and make proper adjustments in the books;
ensure that all taxes withheld and remitted are correctly and accurately recorded to avoid under/over remittance of taxes as presented in the books;
conduct regular review and proper monitoring of withheld and remitted taxes to ensure the correctness and accuracy of the Due to BIR account balance.
Strictly comply with RMC No. 23-2007 dated March 20, 2007, and Title X of the National Internal Revenue Code of 1997. Otherwise, the responsible official/s shall be held liable for the payment of such penalties, interests and surcharges, pursuant to Sections 248 and 249 of the National Internal Revenue Code of 1997; and,
Henceforth, strictly comply with Paragraph 27 of IPSAS 1 to ensure that the Due to BIR account balance is accurately reported in the books of accounts.

We recommended, and Management agreed to instruct:

The CAD and CGSD to –

Identify and make the necessary adjustments in the unreconciled difference totaling P147,708,346.62 between Lapsing Schedule of PPE and RPCPPE for BOS; 

Continue to reconcile records of all PPE accounts as required under Section 53 of GAAM, Vol. III and effect the necessary adjustments in the appropriate reports;

The CAD to provide detailed information of all items listed in the Lapsing Schedule to facilitate reconciliation with the RPCPPE; and

Moving forward, ensure adherence to the provisions and requirements of Section 111 of PD No. 1445, Section 147 of COA Circular No. 92-386, dated October 20, 1992, and Section 491, Vol. I and Section 53 of the GAAM, Vol. III.

We recommended, and Management agreed to require:

The CAD to – 

Provide detailed information on the recorded amount of 
P160.939 million to reconcile with the balance of the lapsing schedule;

Conduct actual physical inventory together with the Inventory Committee of all items listed in RPI to establish the correct balances of  IAs and to record the P183.681 million in the books;


Derecognize the road network projects totaling P4.634 million that were recorded twice, including its depreciation;

Recognize the projects under Paragraph 2.11 amounting to P34.067 million as Other Structures and the P2.519 million as Sewer System in the books upon validation of records; 


Maintain complete and updated ledger cards and subsidiary records;


Update the lapsing schedule to support the computation of depreciation expense for each IA component at the end of the year; 


Continue to reconcile records with CGSD and/or City Engineering Building Officials Department (CEBOD) for all PPE accounts as required under Section 491 of GAAM, Vol. I;

The CGSD to –

Keep complete and updated property cards, Local Road Inventory and Road Map; 

Continue to reconcile records for all PPE accounts as required under Section 491 of GAAM, Vol. I;


Coordinate with CEBOD in conducting an actual physical inventory of all items listed in the RPI and update the RPCPPE accordingly; and


Moving forward, strictly comply with the requirements of Section 491 of GAAM, Vol. I and COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:

Require the CAD to –

Immediately evaluate the discrepancies identified between Lapsing Schedule and the RPCPPE and effect the necessary adjustments to take up reconciling items noted and establish an accurate balance of the MVs and OTE accounts;

Prepare/locate the necessary supporting documents of the donated MVs and recognize in the books the cost upon validation of the items;

Prepare an adjusting entry on the identified misclassified MV items and adequately record in the books all properties according to the Chart of Accounts;

Require the CGSD to –

Prepare and issue updated PAR to the recipient of the MVs every three years or every time there is a change in accountable officer or custodian of the property;

Facilitate the yearly registration of all MVs to avoid unnecessary penalties and charges imposed by the LTO; and

Continuously conduct a reconciliation of records for all PPE accounts as required in the above rules and regulations and effect the necessary adjustments in the appropriate reports.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:

Require the Appraisal Committee to expedite the appraisal of all properties included in the RPCPPE without cost for the subsequent recording of the same in the City’s books of accounts;

Direct the CGSD to exclude in the RPCPPE all lands under the City’s “Land for the Landless” housing program and maintain a separate inventory record of the said lands for proper monitoring;

Instruct the CAD and the CGSD to maintain PPELC and PCs, respectively, for each category of PPE, conduct quarterly reconciliation of records and investigate the discrepancies noted; and

Trace the records/ documents of the two TCTs to establish ownership of the parcels of land and, if found to be legally owned by the City, expedite titling of the same under the City’s name.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:

Require the responsible AOs to immediately liquidate their existing CAs with the CAD and/or refund the same to the CTD;

Instruct the City Legal Officer (CLO) to issue a final demand letter to the erring AOs and institute available remedies to recover the unliquidated CAs, more particularly to those CAs from 2011 and prior years;

Require the CAD to – 

withhold the salary of erring AOs who failed to liquidate their CAs after the final demand from the CLO;


ensure that all CAs are fully liquidated at the end of each year; 


strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 and COA Circular No. 2012-004;

Instruct the CAD and CLO to consider the provisions of Sections 8.1 to 8.3 of COA Circular No. 2016-05, dated December 19, 2016, for the writing-off of the accounts of those unliquidated CAs whose AOs have passed away or liquidation thereof is highly improbable; and

Require the Internal Audit Services Office to review the City's existing policy in the granting, utilization, and liquidation of CAs. If possible, institute additional measures to provide for more efficient and effective procedures to ensure that CAs granted is immediately liquidated within the required period.

We recommended, and Management agreed to require:

The MHDB to –

conduct an inventory of all housing projects of the City and submit all contracts/MOAs or any legal document used in the computation of monthly amortization and applied interest to each housing project to establish the accuracy of the amount reflected in the CBR; 

prepare the updated CBR to establish the correct outstanding balance of the accounts and submit the report to the CAD as basis for recording;

The CAD to coordinate with MHDB and review the discrepancies noted between the SL accounts and CBR, analyze the entries made which resulted in a negative balance and record the necessary adjustments to correct the reported balance of the Finance Lease Receivable account; and

The CAD and MHDB to conduct regular reconciliation of SL balances and the CBR to ensure propriety and accuracy of the reported balance of the Finance Lease Receivable account.

We recommended, and Management agreed to require:

The Inventory Committee to –

Coordinate with the City’s departments for the conduct of physical count of all inventory items as of June 30 and December 31 of each year;


Prepare RPCI and reconcile the same with the records of the CAD and submit to the COA not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year;

The CGSD to –

Designate an Inventory Custodian per department to: (i) monitor receipts and issuances of supplies and materials, (ii) prepare the necessary RIS, and (iii) update the SC;


Prepare the required SSMIs monthly for submission to the CAD, together with the original copies of RIS, for preparation of the required JEV to recognize the related expenses on the issuance of inventories;

The CAD to –

Monitor the submission of SSMIs for the immediate recording of all issued supplies and material in the books of accounts;

Record purchases of supplies and materials in the appropriate inventory accounts and usage thereof as an expense, upon receipt of SSMIs; 


Maintain SLCs of all inventory accounts for proper monitoring and reconciliation of the accounts; and

Coordinate with the Inventory Committee and CGSD to reconcile their inventory records regularly.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:

Comply with the timely submission of the POs and Contracts as required under Sections 3.1.1 and 3.2.1 of COA Circular 
No. 2009-001;

Submit the Notices of Delivery as required under COA Circular 
No. 96-010 and Section 114(d) of COA Circular No. 92-386;

Ensure that adequate review had been performed in the processing of procurement transactions to prevent, if not eliminate, the duplication of POs that would cause confusion during payment;

\


Ensure that POs and other contracts are duly accomplished, complete, and signed by the responsible departments; and

Strictly comply with the provisions under Sections 3.1.1, 3.2.1 and 4.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 regarding submission of copies of government contracts and purchase orders and Section 114(d) of COA Circular No. 92-386, for the furnishing of Notices of Delivery.

We recommended, and Management agreed to: 

Coordinate with the LBP representative to resolve the issues concerning “rejected” or “in-process” collections and require the improvement of the system to tailor-fit to the needs of the City’s taxpayers and avoid the incurrence of numerous unsuccessful transactions;

Instruct the City Treasurer to immediately issue ORs to successful online taxpayers for the P2,665,307.32 collected using the e-payment system;

Require the City Accountant to record the same to correct the understatement of cash and revenue accounts in the books of the City; and

Strictly comply with the provisions of Book V, Title I, Subtitle B – The Commission on Audit, Chapter 7 - Sections 42 and 44 of Executive Order No. 292 on the collections and recording of collection.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:

Ensure that supporting documents are properly accomplished and signed by the responsible departments;

Submit immediately the lacking documents enumerated in paragraph No. 3;

Stop the practice of processing payments without complete supporting documents; and

Strictly comply with the provisions of Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445 and Section 9 of COA Circular No. 2012-001.

We recommended that the Management:

Instruct the CAD to –

immediately conduct further analysis to determine the nature of unremitted taxes totaling P23,827,505.11, and upon verification, prepare the necessary documentations to settle all unremitted taxes withheld as required under the Revenue Memorandum Circular to avoid being subjected to penalties, interests and surcharges by BIR;

analyze further taxes withheld and remitted in prior years to determine the nature and causes of the negative balance of the      three percent EWT under GF amounting to P6,206,289.49 and make proper adjustments in the books;

ensure that all taxes withheld and remitted are correctly and accurately recorded to avoid under/over remittance of taxes as presented in the books;

conduct regular review and proper monitoring of withheld and remitted taxes to ensure the correctness and accuracy of the balance of Due to BIR account; and

Strictly comply with the provisions of RMC No. 23-2007 dated March 20, 2007, and Title X of the National Internal Revenue Code of 1997.  Otherwise, the responsible official/s shall be held liable for the payment of such penalties, interests and surcharges, pursuant to Sections 248 and 249 of National Internal Revenue Code of 1997.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:

Require the CHRD and CAD to conduct further analysis to identify those contributions withheld in prior years and reconcile the same with the confirmation schedules submitted by GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth to ascertain that the correct balances are withheld and remitted, and proper adjustments are made in the books; 

Remit immediately all verified unremitted withheld premium contributions for both government and employees share and loan repayments, upon verification by CHRD and CAD, as required under Section 14 of RA No. 8291 and its IRR, RA No. 9679 and its IRR, and Section 18(b), Rule III, Title II of the Revised IRR of the National Health Insurance Act of 2013;

Immediately conduct further analysis to identify those contributions withheld and remitted in prior years to determine the causes of the understatement in beginning balance and make proper adjustments in the books; and 

Moving forward, strictly comply with Sections 14 of RA No. 8291 and its IRR, Section 3a. Rule VII and Section 1, Paragraph 3, Rule XII of the IRR of RA No. 9697 or the HDMF Law of 2009 and HDMF Circular No. 275, series of 2010, Section 18 (b), Rule III, Title II of the Revised IRR of the National Health Insurance 
Act of 2013, and PhilHealth Circular No. 0001, series of 2014.

We recommended that:
a. The Inventory Committee and the CAD reconcile, analyze and investigate the discrepancy between the book balance and the RPCPPE to identify the causes of the errors/deficiencies noted and make the necessary adjustments, if any;
b.  The City Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting entry to correct the errors in the recognition of the Public Infrastructure (PI) accounts and ensure that all completed PIs during the year and the corresponding depreciation are fully recognized in the appropriate asset accounts;
c. The Inventory Committee provide the City Accountant the list of demolished properties as basis in the derecognition of the said properties in the books; and
d. The Appraisal Committee assess the current fair value of the donated/procured properties without cost for recording in the books.

We recommended that Management require:
The City Accounting Department to -
Coordinate with the CTD to secure the necessary debit and credit memos from the concerned banks to support the unrecorded reconciling items;
Prepare the necessary adjustments in the books as reconciling items are identified and documented;
Submit for audit the BRS on a regular basis pursuant to COA Circular No. 96-011 dated October 2, 1996 and prepare BRS for the three accounts without BRS;
Coordinate with the CTD and LBP to identify and ascertain the legality and validity of the two accounts not included in the balance, and record the amount, when warranted;
Coordinate with PVB and investigate the nature of the closed and dormant time deposit accounts and do the necessary action on the non-inclusion of the two current bank accounts in the CIB, as warranted, in order to adjust and correct the balances of these accounts, and also prepare regularly the required BRS; and
The CTD and CAD to make concerted efforts to review and analyze their respective records to come up with reconciled and correct balances.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Market Committee to propose revisions/amendments to the Market Code particularly on the imposition of market fees taking into consideration the current market trends and increasing maintenance cost in the operation of the public market;
Require the Market Administrator to enforce immediate collection of rental fees and corresponding penalties/surcharges from delinquent stallholders, through (a) issuance of demand letters to stallholders to encourage the timely payment of rental dues to avoid penalties and     (b) issuance of Notice of Suspension and/or Eviction to stallholders who habitually violate the provisions set forth by the Market Code;
Instruct the Market Administrator and the City Treasurer to prepare and submit Report on Stallholders’ Arrearages to the CAD as basis in the proper recording and monitoring of the accounts; and
Require the City Accountant to establish the appropriate receivable account to recognize the amount of accumulated uncollected market rental fees and charges.

We recommended that Management direct:
The HRMD to reconcile their records with the GSIS, PAG-IBIG and PhilHealth and update their records accordingly;
The City’s electronic remittance file officer to furnish the payroll preparer the copies of the GSIS, PAG-IBIG and PhilHealth monthly billings to ensure that the correct amount of premium contributions and loan amortizations deducted in the payroll are based on the said billings;
The City Accountant to –
Reconcile monthly the actual deductions in the payroll against the billing statements and/or confirmation statements and the amount remitted to avoid discrepancies; and
Conduct detailed review and analysis and, if warranted, adjust the accounts that have been long outstanding/unremitted in the books of the GF and SEF.

We recommended that Management:
Demand from persons determined liable to settle the disallowances and charges which became final and executory, send demand letters and withhold salaries in compliance with COA Circular No. 2009-006;
Enforce immediate compliance from concerned persons responsible to settle the suspensions issued by submitting the documents required in audit to avoid issuance of the notice of disallowance;
Require the City Accountant to record in the books the charges and disallowances amounting to P5,740,682.88 and P5,307,775.61, respectively, which became final and executory; and
Direct the City Accountant and the City Treasurer to refund the excess payment/over deduction on settlements made thru salary deduction; and the City Accountant to prepare the Journal Entry Voucher and effect the necessary adjustments to the Subsidiary Ledgers-Receivables, Disallowances/Charges in order bring the account to its correct balance.

11.8	We recommended that Management require:
The City Planning Development Office (CPDO) to strictly comply with the JMC issued by DILG and DBM on the updated guidelines on the appropriation and utilization of the twenty percent (20%) of the Annual IRA for Development Projects particularly in ensuring optimal utilization of the 20% DF which shall partake the nature of investment or capital expenditures;
The CPDO to properly monitor the utilization of the 20% DF and submit report to the DILG through its Local Government Performance Management System, and maintain a database system on the status of implementation of PPAs and on the utilization of the fund;
The CPDO to maximize the utilization of the development fund through adequate planning and identification of priority PPAs; and
The Local Finance Committee to classify the appropriations for the 20% DF in the budget under the capital expenditures instead of MOOE.

13.11	We recommended that Management require:
The MHDB to review and update the Draft Code of Policies in the implementation of the housing program of the City and submit the same for approval to the Local Chief Executive with the conformity of the City Council;
The MHDB to conduct an inventory of all housing projects of the City and determine existence of contracts, if none, execute one immediately;
The Accounting and the MHDB to make a concerted effort in determining the correct amount of the housing projects still booked under the PPE account and prepare the necessary adjusting entries;
The City Accountant to maintain individual ledgers of all housing beneficiaries to monitor the outstanding balances and conduct periodic review and reconciliation of the accounts relative thereto; and
The Information Technology Department to link the records of the Accounting Department, Treasury Department and MHDB, particularly on the billing, collection and recording processes to facilitate reconciliation of records and generation of reports.

16.5	We recommended that Management require:
The CEMD to earmark the financial support of the City to the barangays for the establishment of MRFs  and for the implementation of waste segregation at source;
The SWM Board and the CEMD to enforce strict implementation of the no segregation, no collection policy and to conduct and intensify information campaign for residents/households, institutions and commercial establishments;
The CEMD to expedite the installation of the three-phase electrical power supply to support the voltage requirements of the machineries to be used in the operation of the Citys MRF housed at the NCMH; and
The Liga ng mga Barangay to encourage active participation of its officials through the creation of Barangay Solid Waste Management Committee to support the SWM program by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of recyclable materials from compostable wastes.

17.13	We recommended that Management instruct the LSB to:
Re-examine the flaws in their existing system and enhance its budget authorization procedures in line with the provisions of P.D. No. 1445 and R.A. No. 7160 and its IRR and amendment, to avoid incurrence of overdraft and ensure that all expenditures are duly covered with appropriation and in accordance with the approved budget;
Furnish the City Budget Officer, the City Accountant and the City Treasurer a copy of the SEF budget as basis for disbursements or for issuance of certification of availability of funds and for recording purposes;
Allocate the SEF budget only for eligible and priority programs, projects and activities allowed by law, rules and regulations and encourage schools to make use of the DepEds funds for their regular operations;
Stop paying honoraria of the ALS, ALIVE, Project TEACH and 
E-Customer Service Training Center trainers and officers, unauthorized training expenditures, maintenance and operating expenses of the DepEd Division Office and other expenses not included in the list of priority expenses chargeable against SEF;
Submit supporting documents/legal basis for the payment of expenditures amounting to P1,064,760.50; and
Settle the outstanding loan balance to the GF as appropriated in the SEF budget.
17.14	We also recommended that the LSB and the City Budget Officer, in the preparation of the CY 2018 SEF budget and utilization thereof, ensure that all charges to the SEF are in accordance with the provisions of R.A. No. 5447, Section 272 of R.A. No. 7160 and DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, S-2017.

Create an Inventory Committee to be composed of the third ranking official of the City as Chairman and representatives from the GSD, CAD, Internal Audit and from each office as members;

Instruct the Inventory Committee to prioritize the completion of the physical inventory of all the City’s assets, prepare the RPCPPE, reconcile the result thereof with the GSD and CAD records, and submit to COA for review and verification;

Create the Appraisal Committee who will conduct an appraisal of all existing PPEs without cost for subsequent recording in the books of accounts; and

Instruct the CAD to prepare lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each classification of the public infrastructure at the end of the year in accordance with PPSAS 17.

Take up the necessary entries for the recognition of the 25 percent Public Infrastructures in their corresponding PPE accounts in accordance with PPSAS 17;

Coordinate with the Engineering Department to determine the existing public infrastructures as of December 31, 2016 to correct the balance of the Public Infrastructure accounts; and

Conduct physical inventory to determine the existence of all completed infrastructure projects as of December 31, 2016 and prepare a report thereon to be submitted to the Accounting Department as basis for adjustments, if necessary.

Conduct immediate identification and thorough verification of all outstanding reconciling items not yet taken up in the books in order to establish the correct balances of the Cash in Bank accounts and thereafter furnish the Office of the Auditor copies of Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) taking up the adjustments;

In coordination with the City Treasurer, secure/obtain copy of the certificate of time deposits from depository bank and verify the details of the current accounts recorded in the books but not confirmed by the bank totaling to P67,327,291.57; and submit copy for audit; and

Henceforth, submit for audit the BRS on a regular basis as required pursuant to COA Circular No. 96 - 011 dated October 2, 1996.

Advise the City Treasurer and the City Accountant to exert extra efforts to locate the supporting documents of prior years’ reconciling items and effect appropriate adjustments in their respective records/cashbooks, where necessary, to establish the correct balance of the Cash - Local Treasury and other affected accounts;

Instruct the City Accountant to provide full disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements of the discrepancy and the action taken by Management pending final resolution or outcome of the verification made thereon;

Evaluate the existing ICS and determine effectiveness of control over the Treasury Management; and

Stop the practice of signing checks in advance.

Instruct all the concerned accountable officers and employees to settle their outstanding cash advances by demanding the immediate submission of duly accomplished liquidation reports. Otherwise, cause the withholding or suspension of their salaries for non-compliance therewith;

Require the City Accountant to forward the list of outstanding cash advances to the City Legal Department for appropriate legal action against those erring personnel who continue on not settling their accountabilities/liabilities to the City; and

Enforce strictly the existing laws, rules and regulations governing the proper handling of cash advances and the rendering of accounts by the concerned accountable officers in order to reduce long outstanding accounts.

Institute measures to further enhance controls and assure accuracy of the data and information to be utilized for budget planning, execution and accountability;

Conduct proper review of past collection performances and analysis of the adequacy of the proposed revenue collection targets in accordance with the true intent of local government budgeting to ensure that projections are based on reasonable estimates of income; and

Require the Local Finance Committee to include the beginning cash balance in the Statement of Receipts (LBP Form No. 1) in the determination of the total available funds for appropriation.

Conduct detailed review and analysis and, if warranted, adjust the accounts that have been long outstanding/unremitted in the books of the GF and SEF;

Remit the monthly contributions, premium payments, loan amortizations and other amounts withheld from employees in full, including government share to concerned government agencies within the dates prescribed by the laws, rules and regulations to ensure that employees will enjoy the full benefits from the GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth, avoid payments of penalties and the possible non-approval of employee loans from these GOCCs. Otherwise, the withholding agent should be held liable for the payment of interest; and

Strengthen internal accounting control on monitoring and review of withheld amounts payable to government agencies including government contributions.

Ensure  that  the 20% LGU share from Fire Code Revenue be used strictly in accordance with DBM and DILG Joint Circular No. 2015-01 dated February 12, 2015 and the MOA dated September 9, 2016;

Require the Fire Marshall and concerned City officials to submit the annual Fire Protection Plans and Budget (FPPB) Matrix or List of Priorities/Activities as approved by the Local Chief Executive; and

Require the CAD to stop charging ineligible expenses to the 20% share of the City from the Fire Code Revenue and instead charge to the appropriate fund.

The City Planning Development Office (CPDO) to strictly comply with the JMC issued by DILG and DBM on the updated guidelines on the appropriation and utilization of the twenty percent (20%) of the Annual IRA for Development Projects particularly in ensuring optimal utilization of the 20% DF which shall partake the nature of investment or capital expenditures;

The CPDO to properly monitor the utilization of the 20% DF and submit report to the DILG through its Local Government Performance Management System, and maintain a database system on the status of implementation of PPAs and on the utilization of the fund;

The CPDO to maximize the utilization of the development fund through adequate planning and identification of priority PPAs; and

The Local Finance Committee to classify the appropriations for the 20% DF in the budget under the capital expenditures instead of MOOE.

Comply and ensure that the four (4) thematic areas of disaster risk reduction and management are completely integrated in the LDRRMP as well as in the Local Development Plan, particularly the disaster rehabilitation and recovery programs/projects/activities in the approved AIP to effectively support the disaster risk management activities of the City;

Disclose adequately in the Notes to Financial Statements the non-transfer at the end of the year of the unexpended/unutilized amount of LDRRMF to the Trust Fund account.  The transfer should be made from the General Fund (GF) to the Trust Fund under the Trust Liabilities-DRRMF account as required under COA Circular No. 2012-002; and

Maximize the utilization of the LDRRMF based on the approved AIP to support disaster risk management activities following the policies and procedures on the utilization of the LDRRMF under paragraph 6.0 of NDRRMC, DBM and DILG  JMC No. 2013-1 dated March 25, 2013.

The MHDB to review and update the Draft Code of Policies in the implementation of the housing program of the City and submit the same for approval to the Local Chief Executive with the conformity of the City Council;

The MHDB to conduct an inventory of all housing projects of the City and determine existence of contracts, if none, execute one immediately;

The Accounting and the MHDB to make a concerted effort in determining the correct amount of the housing projects still booked under the PPE account and prepare the necessary adjusting entries;

The City Accountant to maintain individual ledgers of all housing beneficiaries to monitor the outstanding balances and conduct periodic review and reconciliation of the accounts relative thereto; and

The Information Technology Department to link the records of the Accounting Department, Treasury Department and MHDB, particularly on the billing, collection and recording processes to facilitate reconciliation of records and generation of reports.

The City Treasury Department, particularly the concerned disbursing and collecting officers promptly submit the DVs in support of the withdrawals from the City’s LBP accounts. Moreover, submit ORs and other required financial reports together with complete supporting documents to the CAD for proper recording in the books of accounts;

The City Administrator install measures that will facilitate and ensure the timely submission of DVs, ORs, and other financial reports; and

The City Accountant submit monthly financial reports and documents not later than the 10th day of the following month and the year-end financial reports not later than February 14 following the end of the calendar year pursuant to Section 41 (2) of P.D. No. 1445. Henceforth, submit the Financial Statements for the City’s economic enterprises to the Office of the Auditor in accordance with Section 110 of COA Circular No. 2002-003 dated June 20, 2002.

