Conduct review of the programs and projects under GAD plan and the formulation of gender issues consistent with the requirements of GAD;

Prioritize and ensure that all PPAs identified in the GAD Plan of the City are undertaken within the target period and closely monitored as to its progress status so that intended beneficiaries may benefit from the successful implementation of the identified gender issues and concerns; and

Instruct the GAD Focal Point System to coordinate with the implementing departments/offices of the related PPAs to fully achieve the attainment of the GAD objectives.

The LSB, in the preparation of the Annual School Board Budget for the SEF, prioritize programs, projects and activities (PPAs) pursuant to R.A. No. 5447, Section 272 of R.A. No. 7160 and Joint Circular No. 01, S-1998 of DECS, DBM and DILG;

The LSB stop paying honoraria of the ALS, Project TEACH and E-Customer Service Training Center trainers and officers, scholarship grants to college students, unauthorized training expenditures, maintenance and operating expenses of the DepEd Division Office and other expenses not included in the list of priority expenses chargeable against SEF;

The DepEd Division Office submit report to the City Accountant on utilization of all office supplies, tools and equipment for laboratory rooms, medical and dental supplies, etc. for monitoring of procured goods and recording of issuances; and

The City Accountant ensure that all financial transactions are properly recognized in the financial statements.

The City Treasurer, the City Budget Officer and the City Accountant recognize and comply with the requirement of R.A. No. 10121 that the unexpended DRRMF-MOOE shall accrue to the special trust fund for the purpose of supporting DRRM programs and activities within the next five years as guided by the accounting and reporting procedures of COA Circular No. 2012-002;

The City Treasurer transfer the unutilized/unexpended balance of LDRRMF (QRF and MOOE) amounting to P110,026,084.95 to the special trust fund for LDRRM and henceforth, make actual cash transfers to the said fund from the general fund as required by regulations;

The City Accountant, in coordination with the City Budget Officer, review and analyze the expenditures charged against prior years’ unexpended LDRRMF;

The City Treasurer initiate the transfer of fund from TF to GF amounting to P31,915,580.00 which are proper charges to LDRRMF but were erroneously charged to the GF;

The City Accountant take up the necessary adjusting journal entries in both General Fund and Trust Fund books to reflect the correct balance of Trust Liability-DRRM account as of December 31, 2016 and the affected/related accounts; and

The City Accountant, together with the LDRRMO, identify all equipment used solely in disaster response and rescue operations and reclassify equipment that were incorrectly classified to other PPE accounts.

Provide clear policy on the sale of idle lands to collect the 5% Ad Valorem Tax before registering the transactions and perfecting the transfer of ownership to the new owner;

Maintain an updated data base of all idle lands within the City and reconcile its records with that of the City Treasurer’s Office to come up with more accurate and reliable real property records;

Furnish the Office of the City Treasurer with an updated record of idle lands for imposition of additional tax in accordance with Section 239 of R.A. No. 7160; and

The City Treasurer collect the additional Ad Valorem Tax totaling to at least P49,127,142.

Prepare and formulate the yearly plans and programs to support the activities in the attainment of its targets as laid down in the City’s 10-year SWMP and help reduce the contract cost on garbage collection and hauling services;

Include in the yearly plans and programs the formal establishment and frame of reference of MRF in every barangay, segregation at source, segregated collection, and other activities that will ensure the protection of public health and environment. Explore the viability of the Biodiesel Program as income-producing activity, with the assistance extended in the marketing of the products generated from said activity;

Re-start the operation of the MRF facility and encourage the creation of cooperatives with the end view of partnering with them in the marketing and selling of the products from MRF and bio-diesel program;

Consider historical data in the drafting/preparation of contract for hauling services particularly in the estimation/derivation of the contract cost; and

Review the contract on garbage hauling services for CY 2016 and when necessary, consider the estimate of waste materials and other cost components as a significant factor to reduce the cost of services in the subsequent period. Thereafter, reflect the effect of the CY 2016 Mandatory Waste Diversion percentage point to reduce the cost of future contract/s.

The City Treasurer’s Office, particularly the disbursing officers and collecting officers and all other concerned offices of the City to submit promptly the disbursement vouchers, payrolls and official receipts, and other reports with complete supporting documents to the City Accountant’s Office for recording in the books of accounts;

The City Accountant’s Office to install measure that will facilitate the timely submission of disbursement vouchers, payrolls, official receipts, accounting reports and financial statements within the prescribed period; and

The City Accountant to submit for audit the monthly financial reports and documents not later than the 10th day of the following month, monthly trial balances not later than the twentieth day of the following month, and year-end trial balances, general ledger, subsidiary ledgers, and financial statements not later than February 14 following the end of the calendar year, as well as Statement of Financial Position and Statement of Financial Performance for the City’s economic enterprises.

Require submission of explanation/justification on purchases made through reimbursement totaling P27,086,418 instead of the prescribed mode of procurement;

Complete and adequate supporting documents to establish validity and regularity of the abovementioned expenses, i.e. financial assistance and registration fees to the Philippine Councilors League;

Justification for the grant of two or more financial assistance on the same date to the same recipients totaling P160,100;

Disbursement voucher with JEV No. 1794 dated March 28, 2014 amounting to P200,800 which is not yet submitted to this Office as of audit date; and

Explanation/justification for charging representation expenses incurred by four City officials totaling P2,335,056 and the identification of the program/project/activity (PPA) to which these expenses were incurred.

Refrain from resorting to procurement and disbursements through reimbursement method and observe adequate procurement planning.

Direct the LFC composed of the City Treasurer, City Budget Officer, City Accountant and City Planning and Development Coordinator and the Sangguniang Panlungsod to make the necessary revisions to the supplemental appropriations based on the flaws and deficiencies enumerated above.  The revised supplemental budget should reflect the reduction in the amount available for appropriations and the corresponding allocation to expenditure items;

Restrain from incurring obligations and expenditures chargeable to the 2014 supplemental budget which are not supported with actual realized income;

Direct the LFC to re-examine the flaws and enhance its existing budget authorization procedures in line with the provisions of R.A. No. 7160 and its IRR and amendment, to ensure that only funds actually available is proposed for supplemental appropriation in order to reduce the risk that current operating expenditures subject of the supplemental budget will not be adequately funded;

Direct the LFC to assist the Sanggunian in the analysis and review of the budgets to determine compliance with statutory and administrative requirements as required in Section 316(g) of R.A. No. 7160 and the BOM, that is: 1) prepare the Statement of Additional Realized Income signed by the Local Treasurer and City Accountant and submit the same to the Sanggunian; and 2) prepare checklist on documentary and signature requirements (LBA Form No. 1B), to facilitate review and authorization; and

Require the City Budget Officer and City Accountant to revisit the budgeting and accounting processes for the purpose of reasonably allocating the budget to the specific MOOE accounts and restricting Other MOE appropriation to only the costs of services which cannot be classified under any specific MOOE account.  The Accounting Department should make an independent review of other MOE charges and reflect the actual nature of expenditures in the financial statements, to arrive at fair and accurate presentation of MOOE amounts for the period, which will become the basis of future budgets.

We have recommended that the City Mayor direct:

The City Planning and Development Officer (CPDO) and Local Development Council to formulate and identify the priority programs, projects and activities to be funded out of the 20 percent development fund. Likewise, monitoring and assessment should also be undertaken to ensure timely implementation/completion of the City’s development projects pursuant to Joint Memorandum Circular No. 1, S-2007 and DILG and DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2011-1;

The concerned Officials to maximize the utilization of the development fund through adequate planning and identification of priority programs, projects and activities that are envisioned to help achieve desirable socio-economic development and environmental development;

The officials concerned to avoid and/or stop entering into contracts and implementing projects without valid appropriation;

The Accounting Department to locate and submit for audit, disbursement vouchers and its supporting documents to the payments made amounting to P7,041,944.44 for the 2nd and final payment of the drainage system and street improvement (asphalt overlay) at Pinatubo Street, Barangay Barangka Ilaya for review and validation; and

The Accounting Department to review and analyze the erroneous recording of capital expenditures and take up the necessary adjustments.

We have recommended that the City Mayor require submission of the following from City officials concerned:

Explanation/justification on purchases made through reimbursement totalling P27,086,418 instead of the prescribed mode of procurement;

Complete and adequate supporting documents to establish validity and regularity of the abovementioned expenses, i.e. financial assistance and registration fees to the Philippine Councilors League;

Justification for the grant of two or more financial assistance on the same date to the same recipients totaling P160,100;

Disbursement voucher with JEV No. 1794 dated March 28, 2014 amounting to P200,800 which is not yet submitted to this Office as of audit date; and

Explanation/justification for charging representation expenses incurred by four City officials totalling P2,335,056 and the identification of the program/project/activity (PPA) to which these expenses were incurred.

We also reiterated our prior years’ audit recommendation that Management should refrain from resorting to procurement and disbursements through reimbursement method.  We emphasize that payments should pass through the regular mode of procurement and disbursement procedures as required by existing laws, rules and regulations, and not left to the discretion of the City officials concerned who made such reimbursements.

As in the past, we emphasized that Management should observe adequate procurement planning in accordance with Section 7 of R.A. No. 9184 and strictly adhere to the guidelines in the disbursement of public funds stated in Section 4 of P.D. No. 1445, which are essential in the proper discharge of fiscal responsibility.

We recommended that Management:
Create an Inventory Committee to be composed of the third ranking official of the City as Chairman and representatives from the GSD, CAD, Internal Audit and from each office as members;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to prioritize the completion of the physical inventory of all the City’s assets, prepare the RPCPPE, reconcile the result thereof with the GSD and CAD records, and submit to COA for review and verification;
Create the Appraisal Committee who will conduct an appraisal of all existing PPEs without cost for subsequent recording in the books of accounts; and
Instruct the CAD to prepare lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each classification of the public infrastructure at the end of the year in accordance with PPSAS 17.

We recommended that Management undertake the following courses of action:
Instruct the City Accountant and the City Treasurer to exert extra efforts to locate the supporting documents of these prior years’ reconciling items and effect adjustments, where necessary, to establish the correct balance of the Cash Local Treasury and other affected accounts;
Instruct the City Accountant to provide full disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements of the above-mentioned discrepancy and the action taken by Management pending final resolution or outcome of the verification made thereon;
Evaluate the existing ICS and determine effectiveness of control over the Treasury Management; and
Stop the practice of signing checks in advance.

We recommended that:
The City officials strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 to ensure the proper granting, utilization and liquidation of all cash advances;
The City Administrator implement the internal policy that clearance shall not be given and/or approved for retirement, transfer, resignation and/or travel abroad of officers and employees who have unliquidated/outstanding cash advances;
The City Treasurer, City Accountant and City Administrator compel all regular and special disbursing officers to liquidate their outstanding cash advances both for current and prior years.  In cases of failure to comply, cause the withholding of their salaries without prejudice to the filing of appropriate charges under Articles 217 and 218 of the Revised Penal Code or criminal prosecution, under Section 128 of P.D. No. 1445 in relation to CSC Resolution No. 40676 dated June 17, 2004;
The Office of the City Accountant employ all possible means provided by law for the settlement or recovery of cash advances granted to national/City officials and employees who are already separated from the government service. Management should tap the City Legal Office for assistance, in terms of serving demand/collection letters to employees/parties concerned;
The City Treasurer avoid multiple releases of cash advances and the City Accountant ensure that no additional cash advances shall be allowed unless the previous ones are settled or properly accounted for and/or stop authorizing the grant of additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated accounts to forestall the accumulation thereof; and
The Office of the City Accountant initiate necessary action to request for write-off of outstanding cash advances which could no longer be recovered.

We recommended that:
The City Accountant exercise due care in preparing accounting entries and review charges made to the OMOE account in compliance with COA Circular 2015-009 and PPSAS;
The Budget Department provide details of the accounts pertaining to lump-sum appropriations for Other Maintenance and Operating Expenses account;
The City Accountant submit the required supporting documents for the payment of operating expenses totaling P9,176,000.00 to avoid suspension of the transactions; and
The City Accountant stop the grant of monthly operating expenses without legal basis to Division Chiefs.

We recommended that the BAC Secretariat:
Submit copy of infrastructure contracts to COA within five working days from perfection thereof for review and evaluation pursuant to COA Circular No. 2009-001;
Document and monitor the flow or movement of the contracts to establish accountability for the delays in the submission of contracts for audit;
Observe the procedural guidelines embodied under R.A. No. 9184, particularly, on the procurement process for infrastructure projects to ensure that contracts are awarded to entities capable of undertaking the contract; and
Take appropriate action on the 13 infrastructure contracts where the project implementation is suspended, impose liquidated damages as necessary and enforce sanction against the contractor/s who failed to complete the project without justifiable reasons.

We recommended that:
The LSB, in the preparation of the Annual School Board Budget for the SEF, prioritize programs, projects and activities pursuant to R.A. No. 5447, Section 272 of R.A. No. 7160 and Joint Circular No. 01, S-1998 of DECS, DBM and DILG;
The LSB stop paying honoraria of the ALS, Project TEACH and E-Customer Service Training Center trainers and officers, scholarship grants to college students, unauthorized training expenditures, maintenance and operating expenses of the DepEd Division Office and other expenses not included in the list of priority expenses chargeable against SEF;
The DepEd Division Office submit to the City Accountant report on the utilization of all office supplies, tools and equipment for laboratory rooms, medical and dental supplies, etc. for monitoring of procured goods and recording of issuances; and
The City Accountant ensure that all financial transactions are properly recognized in the financial statements.

We recommended that:
The City Treasurer, the City Budget Officer and the City Accountant recognize and comply with the requirement of R.A. No. 10121 that the unexpended DRRMF-MOOE shall accrue to the special trust fund for the purpose of supporting DRRM programs and activities within the next five years as guided by the accounting and reporting procedures of COA Circular No. 2012-002;
The City Treasurer transfer the unutilized/unexpended balance of LDRRMF (QRF and MOOE) amounting to P110,026,084.95 to the special trust fund for LDRRM and henceforth, make actual cash transfers to the said fund from the general fund as required by regulations;
The City Accountant, in coordination with the City Budget Officer, review and analyze the expenditures charged against prior years’ unexpended LDRRMF;
The City Treasurer initiate the transfer of fund from TF to GF amounting to P31,915,580.00 which are proper charges to LDRRMF but were erroneously charged to the GF;
The City Accountant take up the necessary adjusting journal entries in both General Fund and Trust Fund books to reflect the correct balance of Trust Liability-DRRM account as of December 31, 2016 and the affected/related accounts; and
The City Accountant, together with the LDRRMO, identify all equipment used solely in disaster response and rescue operations and reclassify equipment that were incorrectly classified to other PPE accounts.

We recommended that:
The City Assessor and other concerned personnel:
Provide clear policy on the sale of idle lands to collect the 5% Ad Valorem Tax before registering the transactions and perfecting the transfer of ownership to the new owner;
Maintain an updated data base of all idle lands within the City and reconcile its records with that of the City Treasurer’s Office to come up with more accurate and reliable real property records;
Furnish the Office of the City Treasurer with an updated record of idle lands for imposition of additional tax in accordance with Section 239 of R.A. No. 7160; and
The City Treasurer collect the additional Ad Valorem Tax totaling to at least P49,127,142.

We recommended that the CSWMB undertake the following courses of action:
Prepare and formulate the yearly plans and programs to support the activities in the attainment of its targets as laid down in the City’s 10-year SWMP and help reduce the contract cost on garbage collection and hauling services;
Include in the yearly plans and programs the formal establishment and frame of reference of MRF in every barangay, segregation at source, segregated collection, and other activities that will ensure the protection of public health and environment. Explore the viability of the Biodiesel Program as income-producing activity, with the assistance extended in the marketing of the products generated from said activity;
Re-start the operation of the MRF facility and encourage the creation of cooperatives with the end view of partnering with them in the marketing and selling of the products from MRF and bio-diesel program;
Consider historical data in the drafting/preparation of contract for hauling services particularly in the estimation/derivation of the contract cost; and
Review the contract on garbage hauling services for CY 2016 and when necessary, consider the estimate of waste materials and other cost components as a significant factor to reduce the cost of services in the subsequent period. Thereafter, reflect the effect of the CY 2016 Mandatory Waste Diversion percentage point to reduce the cost of future contract/s.

We have recommended that Management, thru the concerned City Officials and employees, undertake the following:

Prioritize the completion of the conduct of the physical inventory taking of all its property, plant and equipment in the ensuing year through the creation of a Committee for that purpose;



The Committee prepare and submit a complete RPCPPE to COA for verification pursuant to Section 490 of GAAM, Volume I, copy furnished the City Accountant for reconciliation purposes;

Require the Accounting and the General Services Departments to give importance and fast track the on-going efforts in reconciling their records;


Observe proper maintenance of the property cards and PPELCs by providing complete and necessary information on both records to facilitate verification and reconciliation of GSD and OCA records;

Effect the required adjustments after reconciliation of the accounting and property records;


Review the computation of annual depreciation of each PPE account and effect the necessary corrections/adjustments in the accumulated depreciation and depreciation expense accounts for the year; 


Transfer the costs from the Construction in Progress-Agency Assets to the appropriate asset account then to the appropriate PPSAS account;

The GSD furnish the Accounting Department with a copy of the Deed of Donation for purposes of recording the donated assets; and


Require the issuance of ARE/Property Acknowledgment Receipt whenever equipment is issued to the end-user or when there is a change of accountable officer to be renewed every January of the third year after its issuance.

We have recommended that the City Accountant and the MHDB review and analyze the transactions affecting the account and take up the necessary adjustments properly supported with valid documents. Consequently, conduct reconciliation of their records and adjust the accounts accordingly, henceforth, adjustments and/or correcting entries be done periodically to prevent existence of long outstanding unadjusted reconciling items.

We have also recommended that the City Accountant: 

Analyze the transactions on the various housing projects of the City in the light of the requirement of PPSAS 13 and convert/record the corrected balance in the appropriate account;

Keep a record of the subsidiary and/or individual account of the awardees to ascertain completeness and correctness of the account balances recorded in the books;

Determine existence of the accounts and see whether all receivable transactions are valid and covered by perfected contracts on record; and

Enforce collection of the receivable accounts and monitor compliance as to payments made and the recording of the same in the books of accounts.

We have recommended that Management, thru the concerned City Officials, undertake the following measures:

The Accounting Department prepare the necessary Journal Entry Voucher reclassifying the account Other Structures to Lease Receivables to convert the same to the appropriate PPSAS account;

The Accounting Department prepare correcting JEV on the overstatement of depreciation expense;  

The Accountant ensure that proper review and supervision of the work of subordinates is done to preclude errors and omissions and that due care and prudence is observed/exercised in recording financial transactions; and

The MHDB to verify the existence of the Panatag Housing Project, determine its location and the number of units constructed including the recipients of the units when these were awarded.

We have recommended that the City Accountant: 

Monitor the outstanding cash advances of all accountable officers and their liquidations. Create a group/task force to undertake the immediate analysis and reconciliation of the due from officers and employees and advances to officers and employees accounts;

Require immediate liquidation of the cash advances after their purpose have been served and the refund of any unused cash advances, with the official receipt evidencing such refund forming part of the liquidation documents; 

Ensure strict compliance with applicable laws, rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation taking into consideration the prescribed period for the liquidation of cash advances. See to it that no additional cash advance shall be allowed unless the previous ones are settled or properly accounted for and/or stop authorizing the grant of additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated accounts to forestall the accumulation thereof; and
Prepare and maintain complete and updated subsidiary records, such as the complete address of the accountable officers, the specific purpose and other related data for control and monitoring purposes, and from then on, the accountable officers to undertake daily reconciliation of their cashbooks and cash on hand, as well as conduct quarterly reconciliation of the accounts with the record of the Office of the City Accountant.

We have also recommended that legal and/or civil actions available as mandated by law be initiated by the City Legal Department for those accounts that have remained outstanding. Remind all those concerned accountable officers who are still connected with the LGU-Mandaluyong City to submit settlement of their outstanding cash advances, and exhaust all possible means to locate and collect the amount due from those who are no longer connected in the service.

We have recommended that Management direct the Accounting and the Treasury Departments to make representation with the banks/lending institutions for the purpose of reconciling the balances of the account and determining the necessary adjustments, if any, to be taken up in the books.

We have also recommended submission of the following documents/information:

Copy of the Loan Agreements entered into by the City;


Reports on the accomplishments and/or status of the projects undertaken funded out of the loans;


Lapsing schedule (Amortization Schedule), schedule of loan repayments or the debt service arrangements made by the City pertaining to the loan acquired; and

Reconciliation of the Book and Bank Balances relative thereto as of December 31, 2015.

We have recommended that Management:

Require the Project Engineer and/or concerned City Officials to ensure that all items of works involved are included in the individual program of works of the project, to deter incurrence of possible additional work items for the project to be implemented and conduct actual pre-site inspection. The agency’s report should establish justification(s) for any Change Order and/or Extra Work Order for such additional work items involved, particularly, as to the quantities that were not included during the preparation of individual program of works on the particular project;

Observe the procedural guidelines embodied under Annex E of the IRR of R.A. 9184, otherwise known as The Government Procurement Reform Act (GPRA), particularly on the condition pertaining to variation orders – change order/extra work order undertaken by the City;

Design/set-up specific written policy on the submission of documents and its integral parts upon approval of a perfected contract, and to furnish the Office of the Auditor a copy of  the contract/s and its supporting documents within five (5) working days for review in accordance with COA Circular No. 87-278 dated November 12, 1987; and

Submit colored photographs taken (before, on-going and after) duly labelled, and when possible, the date and time it was taken would appear on the bottom or elsewhere in the picture, for all projects completed/implemented by the City.

We have recommended that Management undertake the following courses of action:

Submission of copy of the duly approved 10-year SWMP of the City that will serve as a guide to the City’s implementation of the ESWMS i.e., segregation at source, segregated collection, establishment of MRF and other activities that will ensure the protection of public health and environment that may generate funds for the City that will eventually help in the payment for the garbage hauling services;

Include in the SWMP the formal establishment and frame of reference of MRF in every barangay. Explore the viability of the Biodiesel Program as income-producing activity, with the assistance extended in the marketing of the products generated from said activity;

Re-start the operation of the MRF and encourage the creation of cooperatives with the end view of partnering with them in the marketing and selling of the products from MRF and bio-diesel program;

Encourage the participation of CEMD and/or consider the data they gathered in the drafting/preparation of contract for hauling services particularly in the estimation/derivation of the contract cost; and

Review the contract on garbage hauling services for CY 2015 and consider the estimate of waste materials as a significant factor to reduce the cost of services in the succeeding period. Thereafter, reflect the effect of the CY 2015 Mandatory Waste Diversion percentage point to reduce the cost of future contract/s.

We have recommended that the City Mayor:

Require the City Accountant to fast track the reconciliation of the Due to PDAF account with the Treasury records and other related accounts, and immediately remit the outstanding PDAF to the Bureau of Treasury;

Require the City Accountant to review and analyze the long outstanding balances of Due to Other NGAs account, for adjustment, if warranted and/or immediate liquidation by City officials concerned;

Gather and furnish the Office of the Auditor with relevant information and documents to substantiate the nature and purpose of the long outstanding balance of P1,040,105 and determine the required adjusting entries; and

Perform immediate review and substantiate the remaining long outstanding balance of Due to GOCCs-MMDA amounting to P12,937,015 and reconcile the said balance with the amount recorded in the books of MMDA of P55,439,544.

We have recommended that the City Mayor direct the City Treasurer to transfer the retained balance of 15% from the share of DPWH to a separate trust fund account in accordance with DPWH and DILG JMC No. 001.

We have recommended that the City Mayor:

Establish specific written authority designating accountable officer/s to handle or receive revenues and receipts, including the requirement of filing appropriate fidelity bond;

Require the City Treasurer who is responsible for taking custody of and proper management of funds as stated in Section 470 of R.A. No. 7160, to exercise direct supervision over all designated accountable officers and ensure that adequate cash management controls are in place in accordance with Section 29, 30 and 31 of the Manual on the NGAS, Volume I, COA Circular No. 92-382 and the Local Treasury Operations Manual;

Refrain from designating casual or job order employees to collect revenues and receipts. When existing conditions warrant the designation of casual employees as collecting officers, their immediate supervisors should assume full responsibility and liability for all actions committed by said casual employees;

Require City Treasurer and City Legal Officer to take immediate action for the recovery of the amounts lost or misappropriated by subject accountable officers, to form part of the City government funds, and furnish this Office of the action taken, current information and monthly report on the status of the cases as well as amount recovered; and

File appropriate charges against accountable officers who failed to settle their accountabilities with the City after exhausting available administrative remedies, furnishing the Office of the Auditor of such action taken.

We have recommended and reiterated that the City Mayor:

Direct the LFC composed of the City Treasurer, City Budget Officer, City Accountant and City Planning and Development Coordinator and the Sangguniang Panlungsod to make the necessary revisions to the supplemental appropriations based on the flaws and deficiencies enumerated above.  The revised supplemental budget should reflect the reduction in the amount available for appropriations and the corresponding allocation to expenditure items;

Restrain from incurring obligations and expenditures chargeable to the 2014 supplemental budget which are not supported with actual realized income;

Direct the LFC to re-examine the flaws and enhance its existing budget authorization procedures in line with the provisions of R.A. No. 7160 and its IRR and amendment, to ensure that only funds actually available is proposed for supplemental appropriation in order to reduce the risk that current operating expenditures subject of the supplemental budget will not be adequately funded;

Direct the LFC to assist the Sanggunian in the analysis and review of the budgets to determine compliance with statutory and administrative requirements as required in Section 316(g) of R.A. No. 7160 and the BOM, that is: 1) prepare the Statement of Additional Realized Income signed by the Local Treasurer and City Accountant and submit the same to the Sanggunian; and 2) prepare checklist on documentary and signature requirements (LBA Form No. 1B), to facilitate review and authorization; and

Require the City Budget Officer and City Accountant to revisit the budgeting and accounting processes for the purpose of reasonably allocating the budget to the specific MOOE accounts and restricting Other MOE appropriation to only the costs of services which cannot be classified under any specific MOOE account.  The Accounting Department should make an independent review of other MOE charges and reflect the actual nature of expenditures in the financial statements, to arrive at fair and accurate presentation of MOOE amounts for the period, which will become the basis of future budgets.

We have recommended that the following courses of action be undertaken:

In the absence of amendment to the Market and Revenue Codes, the City Mayor should direct the market administrator to recompute the monthly rentals based on the approved rates and immediately implement the correct rates;

The City Mayor should direct the market administrator to enforce the provision of the Market Code on the collection of entry fees to owners engaged in the wholesale business of meat products and vehicles at the driveway carrying fruits, vegetables, grocery and general merchandise.  The stallholders should be properly informed and a market collector should be assigned to closely monitor collection of such fees;

Make representation with Macro Funders and Development Corporation on the collection of entry fees from stallholders that should rightfully accrue to the benefit of the City;

In revisiting the existing Market Code, the Market Committee should consider proposing the revision of the market rates and fees taking into consideration the current market trends and the increasing maintenance cost of the public market, given that it has been twenty years since its implementation;

The City Mayor should direct the Market Administrator to implement the imposition of penalty for non-payment of rental and other charges and cancellation of the award/lease for failure to pay within one month from the date fixed as stated in the Ordinance;

Incorporate in the recommended amendment to the Market Code, revision of the existing application to lease by incorporating penalty clause that will govern the imposition of penalty for late payment and cancellation of award/lease for non-payment as envisioned in the Code.  It should also include all terms and conditions that will fulfill the requisites of a valid contract such as consent of the contracting parties; and

The City Mayor should direct the Treasurer to review the schedule of arrears to establish the validity and correctness, and demand immediate collection from concerned stallholders.  Thereafter, all succeeding delinquent accounts should be subjected to penalties and surcharges pursuant to Section 10 of the Market Code.
